What a unique church! It's tower is also noticable from far away and I finally got chance to visit today. Must visit!  Designed by Emile Bois, it was completed in 1938. Typical of it's period it recalls Romanesque and Byzantine architecture through its search for the geometry and volume of 1930s, often emphasized by the decoration.

One of the many Churches in Paris, with great architecture and a beautiful fa√ßade.

What a beautiful church. I walked on the Avenue Marceau on the afternoon of Assumption Day on August 15th and visited Saint-Pierre de Chaillot. It was peaceful and solemn, and the carvings outside the church were so beautiful. The carvings on the columns inside are completely different from other ordinary churches, and it is well worth a visit.  I sat quietly in the church for half an hour and fully felt the place.  If you continue walking forward, you will reach the Arc de Triomphe.

One of the few large churches built in the 1930s in Paris.  It is severe, with its gray concrete, its absence of large frescoes, and resembles, through its vaults, those large funerary monuments built near Verdun (the Douaumont ossuary, in particular) but there is something solemn and beauty in this sobriety.  I was unable to see the facade, which is currently being restored.

A large and silent place, where meditation for prayer is favored by the elegant simplicity of the interiors and the quiet. Evidently well managed (a defibrillator is also available and the entrance for people with disabilities is at the back, convenient and always available) it is a place open to hospitality, a Parisian point of reference for the Italian and Spanish-speaking communities. The choir is excellent and the commitment (and intelligence) of the priest who follows the Italian-speaking faithful is remarkable. A crypt is attached. Masses in Italian: Saturday at 6.00pm in the crypt and at 6.30pm in the Church; Sunday at 5.30pm in the church. At 7.00 pm on Sunday it is possible to participate in a Gregorian Mass. An experience without pomp but spiritually intense, thanks to the singing of some parts also in Latin and the sound of the magnificent organ present in the Church.
